{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01LSjy4oqR6w9tFcGqFtKmdv","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package com.ibm.websphere.samples.daytrader.events;\n     2→\n     3→public record MarketSummaryUpdateEvent(String payload) {}\n     4→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01MYxW4uTPhXMTMU8Sq7ArXi","session_id":"56efa089-e1a8-4ed6-8ae5-0ef3f5d72aa6","uuid":"53d8b1f5-95a8-463a-9311-294c82dee52a"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_011mA7JYQrEJLBopLropUXUy","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→-- DayTrader initial seed data for Quarkus/Hibernate\n     2→-- The keygenejb table is used by KeySequenceDirect for ID generation\n     3→-- This table is NOT a JPA entity, so we need to create it manually\n     4→\n     5→CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS KEYGENEJB (\n     6→  KEYVAL INTEGER NOT NULL,\n     7→  KEYNAME VARCHAR(250) NOT NULL,\n     8→  CONSTRAINT PK_KEYGENEJB PRIMARY KEY (KEYNAME)\n     9→);\n    10→\n    11→INSERT INTO KEYGENEJB (KEYNAME, KEYVAL) VALUES ('account', 0);\n    12→INSERT INTO KEYGENEJB (KEYNAME, KEYVAL) VALUES ('holding', 0);\n    13→INSERT INTO KEYGENEJB (KEYNAME, KEYVAL) VALUES ('order', 0);\n    14→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01MYxW4uTPhXMTMU8Sq7ArXi","session_id":"56efa089-e1a8-4ed6-8ae5-0ef3f5d72aa6","uuid":"7838470f-b086-4d66-a61d-5f0eca94418e"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01UrNw518myjciBM14m1JpHK","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→-- DayTrader schema for H2\n     2→-- Intentionally idempotent (safe to run on every startup).\n     3→\n     4→CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS ACCOUNTPROFILEEJB (\n     5→  ADDRESS VARCHAR(250),\n     6→  PASSWD VARCHAR(250),\n     7→  USERID VARCHAR(250) NOT NULL,\n     8→  EMAIL VARCHAR(250),\n     9→  CREDITCARD VARCHAR(250),\n    10→  FULLNAME VARCHAR(250),\n    11→  CONSTRAINT PK_ACCOUNTPROFILEEJB PRIMARY KEY (USERID)\n    12→);\n    13→\n    14→CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS KEYGENEJB (\n    15→  KEYVAL INTEGER NOT NULL,\n    16→  KEYNAME VARCHAR(250) NOT NULL,\n    17→  CONSTRAINT PK_KEYGENEJB PRIMARY KEY (KEYNAME)\n    18→);\n    19→\n    20→MERGE INTO KEYGENEJB (KEYNAME, KEYVAL) KEY (KEYNAME) VALUES ('account', 0);\n    21→MERGE INTO KEYGENEJB (KEYNAME, KEYVAL) KEY (KEYNAME) VALUES ('holding', 0);\n    22→MERGE INTO KEYGENEJB (KEYNAME, KEYVAL) KEY (KEYNAME) VALUES ('order', 0);\n    23→\n    24→CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS ACCOUNTEJB (\n    25→  CREATIONDATE TIMESTAMP,\n    26→  OPENBALANCE DECIMAL(14, 2),\n    27→  LOGOUTCOUNT INTEGER NOT NULL,\n    28→  BALANCE DECIMAL(14, 2),\n    29→  ACCOUNTID INTEGER NOT NULL,\n    30→  LASTLOGIN TIMESTAMP,\n    31→  LOGINCOUNT INTEGER NOT NULL,\n    32→  PROFILE_USERID VARCHAR(250),\n    33→  CONSTRAINT PK_ACCOUNTEJB PRIMARY KEY (ACCOUNTID)\n    34→);\n    35→\n    36→CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS QUOTEEJB (\n    37→  LOW DECIMAL(14, 2),\n    38→  OPEN1 DECIMAL(14, 2),\n    39→  VOLUME DOUBLE NOT NULL,\n    40→  PRICE DECIMAL(14, 2),\n    41→  HIGH DECIMAL(14, 2),\n    42→  COMPANYNAME VARCHAR(250),\n    43→  SYMBOL VARCHAR(250) NOT NULL,\n    44→  CHANGE1 DOUBLE NOT NULL,\n    45→  CONSTRAINT PK_QUOTEEJB PRIMARY KEY (SYMBOL)\n    46→);\n    47→\n    48→CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS HOLDINGEJB (\n    49→  PURCHASEPRICE DECIMAL(14, 2),\n    50→  HOLDINGID INTEGER NOT NULL,\n    51→  QUANTITY DOUBLE NOT NULL,\n    52→  PURCHASEDATE TIMESTAMP,\n    53→  ACCOUNT_ACCOUNTID INTEGER,\n    54→  QUOTE_SYMBOL VARCHAR(250),\n    55→  CONSTRAINT PK_HOLDINGEJB PRIMARY KEY (HOLDINGID)\n    56→);\n    57→\n    58→CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS ORDEREJB (\n    59→  ORDERFEE DECIMAL(14, 2),\n    60→  COMPLETIONDATE TIMESTAMP,\n    61→  ORDERTYPE VARCHAR(250),\n    62→  ORDERSTATUS VARCHAR(250),\n    63→  PRICE DECIMAL(14, 2),\n    64→  QUANTITY DOUBLE NOT NULL,\n    65→  OPENDATE TIMESTAMP,\n    66→  ORDERID INTEGER NOT NULL,\n    67→  ACCOUNT_ACCOUNTID INTEGER,\n    68→  QUOTE_SYMBOL VARCHAR(250),\n    69→  HOLDING_HOLDINGID INTEGER,\n    70→  CONSTRAINT PK_ORDEREJB PRIMARY KEY (ORDERID)\n    71→);\n    72→\n    73→CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS ACCOUNT_USERID ON ACCOUNTEJB(PROFILE_USERID);\n    74→CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS HOLDING_ACCOUNTID ON HOLDINGEJB(ACCOUNT_ACCOUNTID);\n    75→CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS ORDER_ACCOUNTID ON ORDEREJB(ACCOUNT_ACCOUNTID);\n    76→CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS ORDER_HOLDINGID ON ORDEREJB(HOLDING_HOLDINGID);\n    77→CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS CLOSED_ORDERS ON ORDEREJB(ACCOUNT_ACCOUNTID, ORDERSTATUS);\n    78→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01MYxW4uTPhXMTMU8Sq7ArXi","session_id":"56efa089-e1a8-4ed6-8ae5-0ef3f5d72aa6","uuid":"491898d8-44fd-4f2a-86d9-d39b85b453ea"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01C3Ff3wZoFiU2u2z9kU6TQA","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→<?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?>\n     2→<!--\n     3→ * (C) Copyright IBM Corporation 2015.\n     4→ *\n     5→ * Licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the \"License\");\n     6→ * you may not use this file except in compliance with the License.\n     7→ * You may obtain a copy of the License at\n     8→ *\n     9→ * http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0\n    10→ *\n    11→ * Unless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, software\n    12→ * distributed under the License is distributed on an \"AS IS\" BASIS,\n    13→ * WITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied.\n    14→ * See the License for the specific language governing permissions and\n    15→ * limitations under the License.\n    16→-->\n    17→<web-app xmlns=\"http://xmlns.jcp.org/xml/ns/javaee\"\n    18→         xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\"\n    19→         xsi:schemaLocation=\"http://xmlns.jcp.org/xml/ns/javaee http://xmlns.jcp.org/xml/ns/javaee/web-app_4_0.xsd\"\n    20→         version=\"4.0\">\n    21→    <display-name>DayTrader Web</display-name>\n    22→\n    23→    <session-config>\n    24→        <session-timeout>30</session-timeout>\n    25→    </session-config>\n    26→\n    27→    <welcome-file-list>\n    28→    \t<welcome-file>index.html</welcome-file>\n    29→    \t<welcome-file>index.jsp</welcome-file>\n    30→\n    31→    </welcome-file-list>\n    32→\n    33→    <error-page>\n    34→        <exception-type>java.lang.Exception</exception-type>\n    35→        <location>/error.jsp</location>\n    36→    </error-page>\n    37→\n    38→    <error-page>\n    39→        <error-code>500</error-code>\n    40→        <location>/error.jsp</location>\n    41→    </error-page>\n    42→\n    43→    <!-- BASIC SECURITY ROLES AND CONSTRAINTS\n    44→\n    45→    <security-role>\n    46→\n    47→        <role-name>testing</role-name>\n    48→\n    49→    </security-role>\n    50→\n    51→\n    52→    <security-constraint>\n    53→\n    54→        <web-resource-collection>\n    55→\t\t\t<web-resource-name>testing</web-resource-name>\n    56→            <url-pattern>/*</url-pattern>\n    57→        </web-resource-collection>\n    58→\n    59→        <auth-constraint>\n    60→\n    61→            <role-name>testing</role-name>\n    62→\n    63→        </auth-constraint>\n    64→\n    65→    </security-constraint>\n    66→\n    67→\n    68→    <security-constraint>\n    69→        <display-name>\n    70→            Constraint1\n    71→        </display-name>\n    72→        <web-resource-collection>\n    73→            <web-resource-name>AllAuthd area</web-resource-name>\n    74→            <url-pattern>/*</url-pattern>\n    75→            <http-method>GET</http-method>\n    76→            <http-method>PUT</http-method>\n    77→            <http-method>POST</http-method>\n    78→            <http-method>DELETE</http-method>\n    79→        </web-resource-collection>\n    80→        <auth-constraint>\n    81→            <description>\n    82→            </description>\n    83→            <role-name>AllAuthenticated</role-name>\n    84→        </auth-constraint>\n    85→    </security-constraint>\n    86→    <security-constraint>\n    87→        <display-name>\n    88→            Constraint2\n    89→        </display-name>\n    90→        <web-resource-collection>\n    91→            <web-resource-name>Protected Area</web-resource-name>\n    92→            <url-pattern>/daytrader/servlet/PingServlet2Session2Entity/*\n    93→            </url-pattern>\n    94→            <url-pattern>/servlet/PingServlet2Session2Entity/*\n    95→            </url-pattern>\n    96→            <url-pattern>/PingServlet2Session2Entity/*</url-pattern>\n    97→            <url-pattern>/PingServlet2Session2Entity</url-pattern>\n    98→            <http-method>GET</http-method>\n    99→            <http-method>PUT</http-method>\n   100→            <http-method>POST</http-method>\n   101→            <http-method>DELETE</http-method>\n   102→        </web-resource-collection>\n   103→        <web-resource-collection>\n   104→            <web-resource-name>Protected Area 2</web-resource-name>\n   105→            <url-pattern>/daytrader/servlet/TradeScenarioServlet/*\n   106→            </url-pattern>\n   107→            <url-pattern>/servlet/TradeScenarioServlet/*</url-pattern>\n   108→            <url-pattern>/TradeScenarioServlet/*</url-pattern>\n   109→            <url-pattern>TradeScenarioServlet</url-pattern>\n   110→            <http-method>GET</http-method>\n   111→            <http-method>PUT</http-method>\n   112→            <http-method>POST</http-method>\n   113→            <http-method>DELETE</http-method>\n   114→        </web-resource-collection>\n   115→        <web-resource-collection>\n   116→            <web-resource-name>Protected Area 3</web-resource-name>\n   117→            <url-pattern>/daytrader/servlet/TradeAppServlet/*\n   118→            </url-pattern>\n   119→            <url-pattern>/servlet/TradeAppServlet/*</url-pattern>\n   120→            <url-pattern>/TradeAppServlet/*</url-pattern>\n   121→            <url-pattern>/daytrader/app/*</url-pattern>\n   122→            <url-pattern>/daytrader/app</url-pattern>\n   123→            <url-pattern>/daytrader/*</url-pattern>\n   124→            <url-pattern>/app</url-pattern>\n   125→            <url-pattern>/*</url-pattern>\n   126→            <http-method>GET</http-method>\n   127→            <http-method>PUT</http-method>\n   128→            <http-method>POST</http-method>\n   129→            <http-method>DELETE</http-method>\n   130→        </web-resource-collection>\n   131→        <auth-constraint>\n   132→            <description>\n   133→            </description>\n   134→            <role-name>grp1</role-name>\n   135→            <role-name>grp2</role-name>\n   136→            <role-name>grp3</role-name>\n   137→            <role-name>grp4</role-name>\n   138→            <role-name>grp5</role-name>\n   139→            <role-name>webSecOnly</role-name>\n   140→        </auth-constraint>\n   141→    </security-constraint>\n   142→    <security-role>\n   143→        <description>\n   144→            All Authenticated Users\n   145→        </description>\n   146→        <role-name>AllAuthenticated</role-name>\n   147→    </security-role>\n   148→    <security-role>\n   149→        <description>\n   150→            Group 1\n   151→        </description>\n   152→        <role-name>grp1</role-name>\n   153→    </security-role>\n   154→    <security-role>\n   155→        <description>\n   156→            Group 2\n   157→        </description>\n   158→        <role-name>grp2</role-name>\n   159→    </security-role>\n   160→    <security-role>\n   161→        <description>\n   162→            Group 3\n   163→        </description>\n   164→        <role-name>grp3</role-name>\n   165→    </security-role>\n   166→    <security-role>\n   167→        <description>\n   168→            Group 4\n   169→        </description>\n   170→        <role-name>grp4</role-name>\n   171→    </security-role>\n   172→    <security-role>\n   173→        <description>\n   174→            Group 5\n   175→        </description>\n   176→        <role-name>grp5</role-name>\n   177→    </security-role>\n   178→    <security-role>\n   179→        <description>\n   180→            WebSecOnly\n   181→        </description>\n   182→        <role-name>webSecOnly</role-name>\n   183→    </security-role>\n   184→\n   185→    <login-config>\n   186→\n   187→        <auth-method>BASIC</auth-method>\n   188→\n   189→    </login-config>\t  -->\n   190→</web-app>\n   191→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST re