{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_013gz5Nnm2EmtkCeSSeX1M4J","type":"tool_result","content":"Caused by: java.lang.RuntimeException: No such user: uid:2409\nCaused by: java.lang.RuntimeException: No such user: uid:9321\nCaused by: java.lang.RuntimeException: No such user: uid:0","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"56efa089-e1a8-4ed6-8ae5-0ef3f5d72aa6","uuid":"b67dea83-a5bc-47ba-9c27-5669e160576e"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_01MCh2P6Noe5dqwnWT6sPcC7","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Even `uid:0` is not found via JPA `entityManager.find()`. The DB build uses JDBC (`TradeDirect` or a similar direct service), but the JPA EntityManager can't find them. This suggests the data was written to a different database or the JPA entities don't map to the same tables.\n\nLet me check if the JPA entity tables and the JDBC tables are the same. The buildDB uses direct JDBC SQL to create tables and populate data, while JPA creates its own tables via `drop-and-create`. Since we use `drop-and-create`, Hibernate creates tables at startup, and then the JDBC `buildDB` inserts data using the JDBC `DataSource`. They should use the same H2 database...\n\nUnless Hibernate's `drop-and-create` re-creates the tables AFTER the data has been populated... but no, the schema generation happens at startup, before the request.\n\nThe issue might be that buildDB creates tables with names that don't match the JPA entity table names. Let me check the entity mappings:"}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":169,"cache_read_input_tokens":145856,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":169,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":411},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"56efa089-e1a8-4ed6-8ae5-0ef3f5d72aa6","uuid":"2b100edd-ce0d-4312-bfba-d1c7d9a86d0a"}
